<HEADLINE>
<P>
OTHER COMMENTARY / EXCERPTS; 
</P>
<P>
GINGRICH'S CORRUPTION ARGUMENT IS SO MUCH MALARKEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RAYMOND PRICE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jim Wright's downfall will be healthy if Congress's zeal for ethical witch 
hunts dies with his speakership. Yes, we should encourage high standards of 
personal ethics by those in government. But the way to get high standards is to 
get good people, and the present malicious mania for minutiae drives away from 
government the best of those we should strive to get into government. The best 
don't need a 6-foot shelf of law books to tell right from wrong. And their 
interest is in serious governance, not the politics of competitive sanctimony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
