NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The enforcement staff of the National Collegiate Athletic Assn. maintains that 
Kentucky assistant basketball coach Dwayne Casey sent $1,000 to the father of a 
recruit last year, Casey's attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
"The enforcement staff has not changed its position," attorney Joe Bill 
Campbell said during a mid-afternoon break in the NCAA Committee on Infractions 
hearing. Casey has denied sending the money to Claud Mills, father of Chris 
Mills of L.A. Fairfax High School. Mills is a freshman at Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
Also, three charges were dropped, including one that alleged L.A. Fairfax 
recruit Sean Higgins, now attending Michigan, was offered money and was 
improperly recruited by Casey. 
</P>
